title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch HK91A2 7.62 1982 PRE-BAN
postcontent: for sale  HK91 is the semi-automatic-only version of the infamous H&K G3A3 automatic battle rifle manufactured by Heckler & Koch GmbH. The HK91 is the renamed and slightly updated HK41 that fires the 7.62x51mm NATO round and was imported into the United States from 1974-1989. The HK91, like the HK41, was also marketed to civilians however, in order to comply with US firearm regulations, slight modifications had to be made to the HK91 to prevent full-auto customizations. Today, the HK91 model is a highly sought-after collector item due to the limited amount of imported rifles that made it to the US. Comes with two 20 round mags. I have owned this rifle since new, it is a safe queen in EXCELLENT condition having fired less than 50 rounds.

title: For Sale:  Remington UMC Model 51
postcontent: Rare Remington UMC (Union Metalic Cartridge) Company Model 51 in 32 cal. Serial number PA 65158 (PA stands for Pederson Automatic) indicating the gun was made in 1923-1925.  John Pederson worked for Remington and was a rival designer to John Browning in this time era of the early 1900's.   These guns were made from 1918-1927. There were 65'000 plus of these guns made. Originally, there were 55,000 offered in 380 cal and later there were 10,000 plus offered in 32 cal. This gun has the Remington trademark engraved on the right side of the frame and an anchor proof mark on the right side of the trigger guard. The bluing is still at 95%-98%. There are some reflections from the flash on my camera making it look like the bluing is worn on the slide, but this is not the case. The barrel is perfect and shiny. The grips are perfect with no cracks or chips. There are three safety's on the pistol. There is a magazine safety that prevents the gun from firing when the magazine is removed, a second manual safety, and a third grip safety similar to a 1911. Collectors and owners of this gun describe it as having perfect ergomics in the way it fits your hand. It has been called a self aiming pistol. General George S. Patton was given one of these guns and carried it in his waistband or in a pocket holster in his rear pocket. He had custom grips made with 3 ivory Starrs and later 4 stars when he was promoted. He called it his insurance gun. There is no rust or pitting on the guninternally or externally. It appears to have been fired very little in the last 90 plus years. This is a perfect addition to anyone's collection.
